snippet.textDisplay: This song hits hard... my drinking took over my life. Ended up getting in trouble with the law... was facing felony charges... than me and my drinking was bleeding over my sons mom to the point where she had to leave. I lost my place cause of the felony charges. Went to work drank all day at work on the way home noticed this guy didnt stop at a stop sign so I swerved to avoid ended up hitting a tree... got a DUI while on probation. Ended up being homeless had to sleep at work. At hotels for months on end... but as of January 15th I was terminated from both my cases. I can see myself smile again and be someone I know again. The only person I had was a dog my son was taken away...

snippet.textDisplay: Not a bad song. Though, personally, not a huge fan of the chorus. Kinda cheesy, in my opinion. Also, “Once an alcoholic, always an alcoholic” is what we say in AA, there is no “was an alcoholic.” If he’s in recovery he ought to know that. And lets also not forget how he used Mac Lethals addiction against him in his diss tracks, if it were me I’d probably address that at some point, so not to be labeled as a hypocrite. If Tom and Madchild really are in recovery, I wish them both the best. And hopefully this wasn’t just a strategy to get more fans, especially since he dissed other rappers for using such tactics in another one of his songs. That being said, I’m definitely a fan of most of his music thus far. Keep it up.

snippet.textDisplay: I can honestly say that I only drank a few beers in high school (SHS 1987) and I have never done any drugs ever. Look at my profile picture which has not been photoshopped and I am 50 years old, married for 29 years and we have one son who is 15. However, I can relate to people who have an alcohol and drug addiction because they have been my friends and family. I have seen them at their worst, in rehab numerous times, SOBER rarely and then fall back into the same addiction. It's a vicious cycle and some I have seen in a casket. I  am positive that this song will help people and give them hope to get or stay SOBER. The video was amazing too. 🤩

snippet.textDisplay: I've had a drinking problem since i was 16. It only lasted until i turned 18  but man being a kid and having to go through something so isolating instead of asking for help was rough. Alot of people will think this is a troll or something stupid so believe what you want. Shit was hard. I don't know which was worse, coming home when everyone's asleep been worrying about me or when my sister was making sure I didn't choke on my throw up while i was asleep. My mom was always at work and had no clue until I ended up telling her that I needed help. One of the hardest things to do for me was admit I needed help. I felt that since I hadn't died yet, I had it under control. My grandmother was a alcoholic and addict and I thought that since that's what killed her, I wasn't an alcoholic. I let the people I care about suffer for so long because I was so selfish, so unwilling to accept help. It's been 3 months, I finished high school planning on going to college to become a social caseworker and youth advocate. One more anecdote before I leave, every breath is a second chance, but when you stop breathing, your chances ran out. Do something before that happens.
